description:
When the bridge forwards a message to Letta, it should show a typing indicator in the Matrix room while the agent processes. Lettabot does this via adapter.sendTypingIndicator() with a 5-second timeout. The bridge should set typing=true on the agent identity when forwarding starts, and typing=false when the response arrives. Files: src/matrix/client.py (message_callback), src/matrix/identity_client_pool.py.

Reference Implementation (TypeScript - lettabot):
```typescript
// From src/core/bot.ts lines 554-556
const typingInterval = setInterval(() => {
  adapter.sendTypingIndicator(msg.chatId).catch(() => {});
}, 4000);

// From src/channels/matrix.ts
async sendTypingIndicator(chatId: string): Promise<void> {
  if (!this.client) throw new Error("Matrix not started");
  await this.client.setTyping(chatId, true, 5000);
}
```

Lettabot detects when the agent responds with exactly '<no-reply/>' and suppresses the message (does not post to the channel). The bridge should implement the same detection in both streaming and webhook response paths. This prevents empty/unwanted messages from appearing in Matrix rooms. Files: src/matrix/streaming.py, src/bridges/letta_matrix_bridge.py, src/letta/webhook_handler.py.

Reference Implementation (TypeScript - lettabot):
```typescript
// From src/core/bot.ts lines 525-531
if (response.trim() === '<no-reply/>') {
  console.log('[Bot] Agent chose not to reply (no-reply marker)');
  sentAnyMessage = true;
  response = '';
  messageId = null;
  lastUpdate = Date.now();
  return;
}

// Also in the system-reminder for group chats, the hint is injected:
// - **Hint**: To skip replying, respond with exactly: `<no-reply/>`
```

Lettabot disables all tool approvals on startup and before each message (throttled 5 min) via ensureApprovalsDisabled(). It also handles orphaned approvals: detects 409 CONFLICT errors, auto-approves pending approvals, cancels stuck runs, and recovers conversation-level orphaned approvals. The bridge has none of this — it relies on Letta defaults which can leave approvals stuck. Implement approval disabling and recovery in the bridge's Letta forwarding path. Reference: lettabot/src/tools/letta-api.ts. Files: src/matrix/client.py, src/letta/ (new module or extend existing).

Reference Implementation (TypeScript - lettabot):
```typescript
// Throttled check (every 5 min)
private async ensureApprovalsDisabled(agentId, force = false) {
  const now = Date.now();
  if (!force && this.lastApprovalDisableAt && (now - this.lastApprovalDisableAt) < 300000) return;
  const count = await disableAllToolApprovals(agentId);
  this.lastApprovalDisableAt = now;
}

// From letta-api.ts:
async function disableAllToolApprovals(agentId) {
  const tools = await getAgentTools(agentId);
  for (const tool of tools) {
    await disableToolApproval(agentId, tool.name);
  }
}

// 409 CONFLICT recovery from bot.ts:
if (isApprovalConflictError(sendError)) {
  const result = await recoverOrphanedConversationApproval(agentId, conversationId);
  if (result.recovered) return this.processMessage(msg, adapter, true); // retry
}

// isApprovalConflictError checks: error.message includes 'waiting for approval' or 'conflict' + 'approval', or status === 409.
// recoverOrphanedConversationApproval walks conversation messages, finds approval_request_message without matching approval_response_message, checks if the originating run is terminated (failed/cancelled), and auto-denies the orphaned approval.
```

Lettabot detects tool call loops (agent calling > maxToolCalls=100) and aborts the stream with an error message. The bridge's streaming adapter has no equivalent protection. Implement loop detection in src/matrix/streaming.py that counts tool_call events per stream and aborts if threshold exceeded.

Reference Implementation (TypeScript - lettabot):
```typescript
// From src/core/bot.ts lines 584-591
const maxToolCalls = this.config.maxToolCalls ?? 100;
if (streamMsg.type === 'tool_call' && (msgTypeCounts['tool_call'] || 0) >= maxToolCalls) {
  console.error(\`[Bot] Agent stuck in tool loop (\${msgTypeCounts['tool_call']} tool calls, limit=\${maxToolCalls}), aborting\`);
  session.abort().catch(() => {});
  response = '(Agent got stuck in a tool loop and was stopped. Try sending your message again.)';
  break;
}
```
